1
00:00:00,301 --> 00:00:28,687
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:29,157 --> 00:00:33,165
homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble, and fully self-enlightened.

3
00:00:35,771 --> 00:00:39,901
So we're actually coming to the end of our chapter on the human condition.

4
00:00:40,561 --> 00:00:45,171
And this is actually the last bit of quotation from the scriptures.

5
00:00:45,713 --> 00:00:46,896
So I shall read it as usual.

6
00:00:52,445 --> 00:00:59,451
Listeners or monks, remember that when you see this word monks in the scriptures, it stands for everybody who's listening.

7
00:00:59,531 --> 00:01:03,837
This samsara is without discoverable beginning.

8
00:01:04,498 --> 00:01:11,945
The first point is not discerned of beings roaming and wandering on, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.

9
00:01:13,387 --> 00:01:18,632
Now there comes a time, monks, when the great ocean dries up and evaporates and no longer exists.

10
00:01:18,813 --> 00:01:19,953
But still I say,

11
00:01:20,591 --> 00:01:29,063
There is no making an end of suffering for those beings roaming and wandering on, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.

12
00:01:30,644 --> 00:01:36,753
There comes a time, monks, when Sinaru, the king of mountains, burns up and perishes and no longer exists.

13
00:01:36,933 --> 00:01:47,746
But still, I say, there is no making an end of suffering for those beings roaming and wandering on, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.

14
00:01:49,734 --> 00:01:54,819
And there comes a time, monks, when the great earth burns up and perishes and no longer exists.

15
00:01:54,840 --> 00:02:04,188
And still, I say, there is no making an end of suffering for those beings roaming and wandering on, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.

16
00:02:05,608 --> 00:02:11,093
Suppose, monks, a dog tied up on a leash was bound to a strong post or pillar.

17
00:02:11,914 --> 00:02:16,299
It would just keep on running and revolving around that same post or pillar.

18
00:02:16,998 --> 00:02:17,699
So too

19
00:02:17,917 --> 00:02:28,650
The uninstructed worldling regards form as self, feeling as self, perception as self, volitional formations as self, and consciousness as self.

20
00:02:28,669 --> 00:02:38,763
And he just keeps running and revolving around form, and around feeling, and around perception, around volitional formations, and around consciousness.

21
00:02:39,663 --> 00:02:44,650
And as he keeps on running and revolving around them, he's not freed from form.

22
00:02:45,001 --> 00:02:46,524
Not freed from feeling.

23
00:02:46,985 --> 00:02:48,486
Not freed from perception.

24
00:02:48,526 --> 00:02:51,473
Not freed from volitional formations.

25
00:02:51,573 --> 00:02:53,135
Not freed from consciousness.

26
00:02:53,515 --> 00:02:56,361
He's not freed from birth, aging and death.

27
00:02:56,862 --> 00:03:01,811
Not freed from sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection and despair.

28
00:03:02,652 --> 00:03:04,637
Not freed from suffering, I say.

29
00:03:05,718 --> 00:03:06,520
It's a bit heavy, isn't it?

30
00:03:09,671 --> 00:03:12,715
So, here we have some old themes.

31
00:03:13,716 --> 00:03:17,661
This business of samsara has no discoverable beginning.

32
00:03:18,521 --> 00:03:21,664
So, really, that's really just looking at cause and effect.

33
00:03:24,707 --> 00:03:28,592
If you go back on cause and effect, you don't seem to get to a beginning of it.

34
00:03:29,353 --> 00:03:39,003
I mean, in other religious forms, they try to form a beginning by saying, you know, a god started it at some point, but...

35
00:03:39,524 --> 00:03:44,090
From the Buddha's point of view, there's no discoverable beginning for this, right?

36
00:03:44,110 --> 00:03:47,134
Which is awful, isn't it?

37
00:03:47,675 --> 00:03:51,340
It presumes that we've been going round and round like this dog for yonks.

38
00:03:54,223 --> 00:03:57,990
Roaming and wandering around, hindered by ignorance and fettered by craving.

39
00:03:58,009 --> 00:04:01,153
So remember, these are the two points on dependent origination.

40
00:04:02,055 --> 00:04:03,236
It begins by this.

41
00:04:03,570 --> 00:04:12,342
a fundamental not understanding, not knowing, which produces for us a misunderstanding.

42
00:04:12,603 --> 00:04:13,604
And that's the delusion.

43
00:04:14,085 --> 00:04:15,145
What is the delusion?

44
00:04:15,546 --> 00:04:19,312
The delusion is thinking that we are human beings in an absolute sense.

45
00:04:20,012 --> 00:04:27,201
I mean, conventionally, obviously, we're not apes, or at least most of us aren't.

46
00:04:27,221 --> 00:04:30,146
You see some people walking along dragging their knuckles on the floor.

47
00:04:30,966 --> 00:04:33,189
But apart from those...

48
00:04:34,132 --> 00:04:41,557
So we have this mistake, and what the mistake does is it makes us seek real happiness in the sensual world.

49
00:04:42,119 --> 00:04:43,019
There's the desire.

50
00:04:44,461 --> 00:04:47,423
And as you know, this desire leads to acquisition.

51
00:04:47,463 --> 00:04:54,749
We have to defend it, and therefore you get the opposite, the aversion, the hatred, and of course, if the enemy is too big, fear.

52
00:04:55,110 --> 00:04:57,891
So remember, those are your three fundamental dispositions.

53
00:04:58,531 --> 00:05:04,036
Acquisition, acquisitiveness, aversion, and fear.

54
00:05:04,507 --> 00:05:07,209
And from then, well, all human misery stems.

55
00:05:09,952 --> 00:05:12,576
And then he gives us three images, you see.

56
00:05:13,958 --> 00:05:16,380
There's the ocean, there's the mountains, and the earth.

57
00:05:17,382 --> 00:05:25,670
And he just says, well, when all this disappears, see, so we know from science that this earth will disappear.

58
00:05:25,971 --> 00:05:31,478
I mean, at some point, the sun will, what do they call those big red blowout stars?

59
00:05:32,259 --> 00:05:33,180
Supernovae.

60
00:05:33,447 --> 00:05:34,749
That's it, you see, we've had it then.

61
00:05:35,509 --> 00:05:38,194
We have to make sure that we're already inhabiting another planet.

62
00:05:40,737 --> 00:05:52,593
So once we know that the Earth is going to die at some point, and it'll probably die quicker than we think because of our own actions, and so, you know, the ocean comes and then etc.

63
00:05:52,673 --> 00:05:52,834
etc.

64
00:05:52,853 --> 00:05:56,278
But still, this doesn't mean that beings don't go on.

65
00:05:56,879 --> 00:05:58,903
Don't go on, you see.

66
00:05:58,923 --> 00:06:02,086
So this presumes, remember, there's always a presumption that

67
00:06:02,523 --> 00:06:16,740
there isn't just this physical body, there's also the mental body, the mano mea kaya, the body made by the mind, which is within this body and leaves the body when we die.

68
00:06:19,043 --> 00:06:30,757
But remember that that's not to be confused with the nibbana datu, as they like to say in Theravada, the element of nibbana, or that which is the Buddha within.

69
00:06:32,180 --> 00:06:32,259
See?

70
00:06:33,487 --> 00:06:45,264
We begin to understand what that might be the more we meditate and the more we recognize what the qualities are of the one who's observing, that which is observing.

71
00:06:50,411 --> 00:06:58,083
And then we get this image of the dog on a leash tied round and round, just running and running around a pillar.

72
00:07:01,307 --> 00:07:02,028
There's no end to it.

73
00:07:02,048 --> 00:07:03,089
The dog doesn't know

74
00:07:03,322 --> 00:07:04,925
What's tying him to the pillar?

75
00:07:04,944 --> 00:07:05,646
He just keeps running.

76
00:07:08,149 --> 00:07:13,497
He thinks that the faster he runs, the more chance there is of it escaping.

77
00:07:14,418 --> 00:07:17,903
But he doesn't realize that he's tied to this pillar.

78
00:07:18,863 --> 00:07:22,309
So what is this pillar that we're tied to, you see?

79
00:07:22,829 --> 00:07:23,290
It's the self.

80
00:07:24,872 --> 00:07:31,642
That's the pillar, that's the false pillar that we've driven into our existence, thinking that, well, this is what I am.

81
00:07:32,084 --> 00:07:34,987
And therefore, we're always going to run around the demands of the self.

82
00:07:35,509 --> 00:07:36,449
And the self is what?

83
00:07:36,490 --> 00:07:37,310
Seeking happiness.

84
00:07:37,350 --> 00:07:38,793
Seeking happiness in this sensual world.

85
00:07:40,596 --> 00:07:45,543
And this takes us to this whole business of what we think the self is.

86
00:07:46,504 --> 00:07:48,107
So remember there are four positions.

87
00:07:49,088 --> 00:07:51,892
And he has it nicely written here at the back.

88
00:07:52,884 --> 00:07:55,490
So, people regard the former self.

89
00:07:55,569 --> 00:07:57,572
So, I am my body.

90
00:07:57,733 --> 00:07:59,536
That's the materialist position, is it?

91
00:07:59,737 --> 00:08:00,678
I am my body.

92
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:03,805
And it gives an example of a flame of an oil lamp.

93
00:08:04,565 --> 00:08:06,589
And its color are indistinguishable.

94
00:08:06,810 --> 00:08:08,112
So, the flame and the color are the same.

95
00:08:08,132 --> 00:08:11,478
So, a materialist will say, well, I am my genes.

96
00:08:11,819 --> 00:08:12,300
Full stop.

97
00:08:13,682 --> 00:08:16,648
And then somebody says, well, the self as possessing form.

98
00:08:17,134 --> 00:08:21,701
So it's more the images of a tree possesses a shadow.

99
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,625
So the real me is my mind, my heart and mind.

100
00:08:25,685 --> 00:08:27,889
But the body is not my real me.

101
00:08:28,108 --> 00:08:32,394
It's something I'm in.

102
00:08:35,700 --> 00:08:39,884
And then the, sorry, that's something I possess.

103
00:08:40,422 --> 00:09:08,049
but it's not me and then there's the form which is in self so it takes the formless mind as a self within which form is situated so I am this mind of mine this mind heart of mine and within that you find this body so again the image is of a scent in a flower the scent is in the flower but then we think well the flower is not the scent

104
00:09:09,532 --> 00:09:14,942
And then the self is in form in the sense that of a jewel in a casket.

105
00:09:15,361 --> 00:09:18,668
So it's situated within the body, but it's not the body.

106
00:09:19,408 --> 00:09:24,918
So we've got all these different ideas of a self, as to who we are, as to what we identify with.

107
00:09:25,620 --> 00:09:27,864
And that becomes the pillar.

108
00:09:29,046 --> 00:09:32,231
And then we keep running around the demands of this self.

109
00:09:32,870 --> 00:09:38,375
And he goes through his usual way of describing the human being, which are these five khandhas.

110
00:09:38,735 --> 00:09:41,677
So the khandhas are these five aggregates, these heaps.

111
00:09:42,477 --> 00:09:46,881
So it's just a way of saying, it's a way of looking at a human being to see where the problem is.

112
00:09:47,942 --> 00:09:55,149
There are many ways that you can split up the human form, but the way the Buddha does it is to show us where the problem is.

113
00:09:55,789 --> 00:09:57,451
So the first one is the body itself.

114
00:09:57,811 --> 00:10:01,914
There's a whole thing that we call the body, both the physical part of our body,

115
00:10:02,366 --> 00:10:07,893
and the way the mind experiences the body, through feeling, sensation.

116
00:10:08,913 --> 00:10:14,639
So for instance, the nail on my finger here, I mean, I don't know it, do I?

117
00:10:15,380 --> 00:10:17,322
I don't even feel it grow, I don't know anything about it.

118
00:10:17,644 --> 00:10:21,126
But I do know it by the sense of touch, and the fact that I can see it.

119
00:10:23,210 --> 00:10:25,231
But I don't actually know the nail in itself, do I?

120
00:10:27,313 --> 00:10:27,695
Stranger.

121
00:10:29,616 --> 00:10:29,876
Do you think?

122
00:10:32,523 --> 00:10:34,206
I keep going on about, this is my body.

123
00:10:35,488 --> 00:10:36,809
And then there's feeling, of course.

124
00:10:36,870 --> 00:10:39,433
All these feelings, they're me.

125
00:10:40,816 --> 00:10:43,000
They tend to be easier to identify with.

126
00:10:43,159 --> 00:10:45,423
So when I've got a pain, that's me.

127
00:10:46,865 --> 00:10:48,368
Then there's the perceptions.

128
00:10:48,889 --> 00:10:51,613
So perceptions, of course, lead to a lot of thoughts.

129
00:10:51,692 --> 00:10:55,198
So what I perceive, I believe, is actually true.

130
00:10:57,062 --> 00:10:57,702
And in

131
00:10:57,952 --> 00:11:06,748
And through our science, we might even come to the conclusion that what I see is actually the way it is.

132
00:11:07,129 --> 00:11:09,732
So when I see a tree, I believe that that's the way it is.

133
00:11:11,956 --> 00:11:15,261
But in fact, if I take another position, I see the tree differently.

134
00:11:15,822 --> 00:11:17,405
And other people see the tree differently.

135
00:11:17,947 --> 00:11:22,053
But I'm of the opinion in myself that when I look at a tree, that's the way it really is.

136
00:11:25,696 --> 00:11:27,719
And then there's volitional formation.

137
00:11:27,798 --> 00:11:33,005
So these are what we would normally call our emotional thought life.

138
00:11:33,025 --> 00:11:34,947
And of course we identify with that strongly.

139
00:11:36,671 --> 00:11:40,014
I'm not feeling well.

140
00:11:40,456 --> 00:11:41,798
This is my opinion.

141
00:11:42,337 --> 00:11:45,361
And there's consciousness.

142
00:11:45,962 --> 00:11:54,774
So the consciousness there is that I am that which cognizes and which can grasp things.

143
00:11:54,940 --> 00:11:56,841
It's a discriminative consciousness.

144
00:11:57,783 --> 00:11:59,265
So I am that, you see.

145
00:11:59,745 --> 00:12:05,933
So all these identities are part of this idea of who I am, which is this pillar.

146
00:12:08,116 --> 00:12:12,702
And I'm just running and running around this pillar, this self, you see.

147
00:12:14,004 --> 00:12:15,846
And just like the dog, I don't see it.

148
00:12:16,346 --> 00:12:17,168
I don't see the problem.

149
00:12:18,230 --> 00:12:20,812
Not until, of course, you become instructed

150
00:12:21,485 --> 00:12:26,613
So we've all been instructed that there's absolutely no excuse for keep running around this pillar for heaven's sake.

151
00:12:27,854 --> 00:12:39,030
But until we do, then at least, sorry, as soon as we do realize where the problem lies, then at least we don't run around so manically.

152
00:12:41,274 --> 00:12:51,288
We still try and make a break for it and just find ourselves running around is when we get lost in our indulgences and get caught up in hatred and all that sort of stuff.

153
00:12:51,606 --> 00:12:55,350
But at least when we wake up we think, hold on, I'm just running around this pillar again.

154
00:12:57,274 --> 00:12:59,976
And he says there won't be, you know, like, you're just not freed.

155
00:13:00,177 --> 00:13:02,058
Won't be freed from birth, aging and death.

156
00:13:02,399 --> 00:13:07,625
Now remember this birth, aging and death is the birth, aging and death of the self.

157
00:13:10,568 --> 00:13:13,472
The Buddha does not suffer from the birth, aging and death of self.

158
00:13:14,133 --> 00:13:15,274
He's liberated from that.

159
00:13:19,500 --> 00:13:21,461
His body dies and

160
00:13:21,981 --> 00:13:27,370
the Buddha within, remains, goes who knows where.

161
00:13:27,850 --> 00:13:30,254
It doesn't have a lodging.

162
00:13:30,355 --> 00:13:31,296
It doesn't have a state.

163
00:13:32,158 --> 00:13:42,573
But it's understood in Mahayana Buddhism that there is also the Sambhogakaya, the body of delight, which is the angelic body.

164
00:13:43,615 --> 00:13:44,216
It's still there.

165
00:13:45,619 --> 00:13:48,342
But it's not fooled by it.

166
00:13:49,471 --> 00:13:58,541
So remember, whenever you hear in the scriptures this business of birth, aging, and death, it's always about the self, the idea of a self.

167
00:13:58,802 --> 00:13:59,962
And it's happening all the time.

168
00:14:00,163 --> 00:14:01,203
It doesn't happen when you're asleep.

169
00:14:02,826 --> 00:14:06,169
When you're asleep, there's no birth, aging, and death of a self.

170
00:14:07,390 --> 00:14:12,136
And when you wake up, you see, you say, oh, here I am again.

171
00:14:13,357 --> 00:14:14,539
You say that every morning, don't you?

172
00:14:14,559 --> 00:14:16,241
Ding-a-ling-a-ling, oh, I'm here.

173
00:14:17,442 --> 00:14:18,364
Here I am again, you see.

174
00:14:18,630 --> 00:14:24,236
And every time we go through the dependence origination, there's a self.

175
00:14:24,256 --> 00:14:25,837
So we're not always doing it.

176
00:14:26,798 --> 00:14:27,740
We're not always doing it.

177
00:14:29,201 --> 00:14:39,613
But every time we do it, there's a process of being born as me, and whatever me is doing comes to an end, and then there's a death.

178
00:14:39,633 --> 00:14:45,519
And because of that, there will continue to be sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection, and despair.

179
00:14:45,938 --> 00:14:46,679
That's terrible, isn't it?

180
00:14:48,398 --> 00:14:52,943
There will be no freedom from suffering, I say.

181
00:14:52,964 --> 00:14:56,590
So that brings us to the end of this section.

182
00:14:56,909 --> 00:15:14,575
And next week, which is my last Tuesday before Noreen comes, I'll just sort of pull it all together, just this whole business on this section, which tends to be, shall we say, meditating on the dark side of life.

183
00:15:16,798 --> 00:15:37,389
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that you will, by your constant endeavor, cut the leash around that post sooner rather than later.

